            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Simon the son of Ka[- -] the priest of A[rsinoe - - and] Aphrodite, (honours) Ptolemy [- - -] Berenike [- - -].</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>This honorific dedicatory plaque in fine mid-third century lettering from a priest of Arsinoe and Aphrodite presents a number of difficulties of interpretation and reconstruction. Although the upper margin of the stone is preserved together with its left and lower edges, it is unclear how far the plaque extended to the right. The absence of the title βασιλεύς at the beginning of the inscription should indicate that the honorand or dedicatee was the son of a reigning king; a full filiation from Ptolemy and Berenike, however, would require a line length of c. 45 letters (Πτολε[μαῖον βασιλέως Πτολεμαίου καὶ βασιλίσσης] | Βερενίκη̣[ς - - -]), which would exceed plausible completions for the following lines. An alternative might be to assume that Ptolemy and Berenike in lines 1-2 are joint objects of the dedication, but their identification then becomes very uncertain: the later Ptolemy III and Berenike Phernophoros might come into consideration but their association is otherwise unattested and the problem of line length for an appropriate supplement remains.</p>
            </div>
